You can try to at argument liket his 

```
func badMethod() {
    let array = NSMutableArray()

    for i in 0..&lt;10 {
        array.insert(i, at: i)
    }

    for _ in 0...10 {
        array.remove(0)  // &lt;- Extraneous argument label &#39;at:&#39; in call
    }
}
```

You&#39;re using an `NSMutableArray`, so the right method to call on that would be `array.removeObject(at: 0)`. Also, you&#39;re removing 11 elements but only add 10.

That said, this is Swift and you should use native arrays:

````
func betterMethod() {
    var array = [Int]()

    for i in 0..&lt;10 {
        array.insert(i, at: i)
    }

    for _ in 0..&lt;10 {
        array.remove(at: 0)
    }
}
````

